What is the Dowker-Thistlethwaite code used for and how is it determined?</s> 
Dowker-Thistlethwaite code is a symbolic manipulation system used in knot theory to represent different knots. It consists of a combination of positive and negative integers that describe the crossing configurations in a knot. The code is determined by analyzing the crossings of the knot and assigning a set of integers to each crossing based on its mirror image and underpass or overpass position. The code is used to classify knots into families and to study the properties and relationships between different knots.
